	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>France and Germany call for ‘a strong CAP beyond 2013’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In the framework of the ongoing debate and the public consultation on the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) after 2013, in mid September France and Germany presented a common position paper setting out their vision of the CAP beyond 2013.</p><p>Although both countries support ‘the strengthening of a market-based CAP and improved competitiveness’, they recognise the need for a suitable regulatory framework … in order to mitigate the destructive effects of growing price volatility and market crises.’ Against this background, the position paper sets out a range of proposals, including in terms of market tools:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘Current market tools (e.g. intervention and private storage) must be part of a safety net to protect the agricultural sector against the effects of major crises’, but some of these ‘could be improved’. The common position paper proposes the introduction of a ‘clause of exceptional, cross-cutting measures based on existing measures ... [which] could deal separately with market and sanitary issues’.</li>

<li>The ‘need for greater transparency and for stronger negotiating power for producers’ is also asserted; tools for monitoring prices and volume as well as price formation could be improved, and the development of tools as standard contracts, which could create a ‘proper balance between the stakeholders in the added-value chain’, should be reviewed.</li>

<li>In addition, in order to stabilise farmers’ incomes, insurance and mutual fund instruments should be examined and their use made possible by the member states.</li>

</ul>
<p>The common position also makes a range of proposals on direct aid payments, which ‘should continue to play a central role in the future’. Regarding the debate on the redistribution of the amounts between member states, the two countries assert that ‘a single rate for all Europe does not make sense and does not match economic conditions within the EU’; however ‘the sustainability of the member states’ financial position in the EU budget on the basis of the current division of contributions should be taken into account.’ In addition, member states should still be able to maintain some ‘flexibility for specific needs’ and ‘the distribution of payments within each member state’ should remain flexible.</p><p>On issue of the budget, the two member states agreed that it was a priority to allocate ‘[sufficient] resources to the CAP to fulfil our ambitions’, and agreed that the CAP should not be renationalised ‘through a co-financing of the direct aid payments to farmers’.</p><p>Regarding competition with third countries, the position highlights ‘the need to ensure that the competition between EU and third-country producers operates on a level playing field. Each imported product should comply with EU standards. … Revised tools such as promotional tools, more effective controls and, as required, labelling measures’ could be proposed by the EC.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Bundesministerium für Ernährung, Landwirtschaft and Verbrauchschutz et Ministère de l'alimentation, de l'agriculture et de la pêche, ‘Position franco-allemande pour une politique agricole commune forte au-delà de 2013’ (‘Franco-German position towards a strong CAP beyond 2013’, 14 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://agriculture.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/100914_position_commune_FR-DE_francais_.pdf" target="_self">http://agriculture.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/100914_position_commune_FR-DE_francai...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The debate on the CAP beyond 2013 seems to focus mainly on the overall level of the budget and on the level of direct aid payments to be allocated to each member state. For ACP producers, the key issue remains what sort of instruments the EU will continue to use in order to support its producers in the event of a crisis, and whether the use of trade policy tools such as export subsidies will still be demanded when the market situation requires, as happened during the recent dairy industry crisis. Neither this, nor indeed the need to reduce the damage caused by European subsidies to developing countries’ agricultural production, is addressed in the position paper.</p><p>France and Germany’s position on competition with third countries suggests that non-tariff barriers to third-country exports could be reinforced, with the paper seeming to imply that EU standards are insufficiently restrictive toward third countries, whereas in fact imported products need to comply with the same standards as European products. For example, ‘more effective controls’ on sanitary and environmental compliance, as recommended in the position paper, could make compliance for ACP producers even more difficult than it is at present. Against this background, greater ‘aid for trade’ support for ACP producers to comply with increasingly stringent EU food-safety standards could be useful, and would allow ACP countries to operate on a more level playing field with EU producers that are supported by EU direct aid payments for standards compliance. While the ‘promotional tools and labelling measures’ could as well constitute a barrier to ACP exports, they could be taken as an example and implemented in ACP countries that want to develop local agricultural production and consumption, as demonstrated for example by Namibia, with the implementation of its recent policy in the horticultural sector.</p><p>The common position of these two major European agricultural nations also has potential relevance for ACP countries currently negotiating EPAs with the EU, in terms of the recognition of the importance both of groups of countries having recourse to safety-net measures to protect their agricultural sectors to alleviate and avert crises, and of transparent relationships at the different stages of the supply chain, in particular to reduce the vulnerability of agricultural producers.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
